segments.text: Special guest, and we'd go down to their apartments for a lunch, and she'd have a light lunch, very nicely laid out as a kind of special event.
Now, a typical word law reception for a book signing or anything like that would include what?
Well, it would include a lot of drinks.
Of what sort?
Oh, anything you wanted.
Frank's favorites were vodka with bullshot.
With what?
Bullshot, the mixer that you put in vodka.
It's kind of a bloody marijuana.
It's real spicy.
It's got beef bouillon in it.
Bullshot is one word?
I think so.
In quotation marks?
I don't know.
It's a trademark.
Oh, it is a trademark.
Okay.
And bourbon he liked.
But we would have, Rosemary would always have food.
What about desserts?
What kind of favorite desserts?
You know, Frank had a favorite.
I can't remember now what it was.
Don't recall.
All right.
Describe the going away events before the ward laws left.
There must have been some.
Yeah.
Well, I don't remember that.
The most memorable party I remember was when Alfred A. Knopf came to visit.
He was a friend of Frank Wardlaw's from the old days.
And we had a luncheon on the boardroom table in what was then Frank's office.
And we had all of the staff.
And a few family members were there, Rosemary and Ruth Gromyla, and my wife, and Claire, my daughter.
Our daughter went with us.
And our daughter had a place all to herself.
I guess she was four years old at the time.
And they sat her between Mrs. Knopf
and Margaret Ingram.
And so she was across the table from my wife and me.
And she just behaved wonderfully well, was very well behaved.
And everybody commented on what a good girl she was.
And then after the lunch, Chris and Claire and I drove the Knopf's to the hotel in Austin.
where they were going to spend the night before heading back to New York.
So we got to ride with them in the car, and I got to ask Alfred Knopf some questions.
Of course, he was pretty elderly then, and I think he really wasn't paying too much attention.
I think he was dozing most of the way, but at least we got to say that we rubbed elbows with the Knopfs.
Can we take a break for a second?
I need to...
Who were some other famous, in these A&M years, who were some other famous celebrities that you encountered?
Well, I don't think that any were that famous to me, as famous as Knopf.
I think there were lots of Texas
people, of course.
Yarborough, for example, used to be at the Texas State Historical Association meetings.
Ralph Yarborough.
Ralph Yarborough, and let me think.
Well, I can't think of anybody specifically, but
some of the lesser lights, I think.
We were heading toward the Ward Law retirement.
Describe the Ward Law retirement.
There must have been all kinds of parties.
Describe the Ward Law retirement parties.
or the big event?
Well, I can't.
As I said earlier, I don't really remember that.
Well, I do.
Yeah, I do.
It was at Three C's Barbecue in Bryan.
I think that was the Wardlaw's retirement.
And had a huge barbecue.
reserved the whole place just for the press's party.
And I saw that it sat across the table from John Tweetin, I think.
And it was an open bar and all the barbecue you could eat.
And it was quite an affair.
Don't remember a lot about it because of the open bar.
Were there some stories told, you think?
Probably.
I'm sure there were.
And in terms of the style of leading the press, how did Lloyd, how did his style differ from Frank's?
Lloyd was, let the staff do, gave the staff a lot more responsibility than Frank had.
Lloyd was more of a hands-off manager than the single focal point of the press.
And Lloyd came up with projects and did acquisitions.
And then in many cases, he turned those projects over to me to carry through on.
But he was mostly the idea man who developed things.
Lloyd did some really great work for the press in fundraising during those early years.
He was the one who got the funding from the Moody Foundation in Galveston for faculty and non-faculty publications.
We already had the Moody Natural History Series established.
That was one of the revolving funds that Frank Wardlaw had set up.
But the endowment for publications by faculty members, A&M faculty, and a separate endowment for publications by people other than faculty members, were both accomplishments
of Lloyd's in the early 80s.
They have been tremendous helps to this press.
That kind of endowment is something every university press should strive to get.
Describe how those endowments work, those revolving funds.
Well, the revolving funds are different from these endowments.
The revolving fund was set up in a particular subject area, for example,

The Moore Texas Art Series or the Merrick Natural Environment Series, a certain amount of money was provided by the donor, and usually we knew we had books to publish in those particular subject areas.
We knew what we were going to publish.
We'd publish a couple of those books, and then a portion of the income
from the sales of those books would go back into the series fund.
Normally what?
A smaller percentage would go, well, 25% would go into the overhead account of the press.
But 75% of the sales income then would go back into the series fund.
And so it kept it revolving and growing.
If we made the right selection of books, those funds would grow over the years.
Of course, and then the Moody, the two Moody Foundation series, not series, but endowments were just straightforward gifts of money to the university press to be used in any way we wanted.
One fund was for publications by faculty members and the other was for anyone else.
And those funds

grow interest and uh... so we have to to be careful not to spend them down but uh... both of them have grown over the years and are extremely valuable to us now to help us publish books that otherwise would not be financially feasible of the various series funded by revolving funds is there one that has been most notable for its success is there one the moody natural history series i think has done better than
Well, it's done tremendously well.
And the centennial series established by the Association of Former Students has also been a tremendous series.
That one, we've done a wide variety of books in it.
Of course, it was begun to publish the centennial history of the university and the pictorial history, and also the Shewitz portfolio of prints.
But since then, we've also published a lot of other things that
that have nothing to do with the history of the university, but are good Texas history or other kinds of important subjects that need to be published.
So we've been able to use those funds to cover the upfront costs of publishing and production costs, get the books published.
And our selections have been consistently good in that series over the years.
So the fund has grown.
And you said that in leadership style, Frank was more centralized and Lloyd more decent.
In hindsight, which worked better for this press?
Well, they both worked well and at the right times.
It was fine that...
that Frank was more centralized, more hands-on, more do-it-himself.
Because at that time, we were all young and learning.
And it was good to have someone with that kind of experience guiding the direction of the press.
And then after some years, after we had learned our jobs and Lloyd came in, he was able to turn over a lot of the things to us because we had the experience to handle them then.
And then he could
go ahead and do the fundraising and the kinds of acquisitions that he did.
And he's director about how long?
He's director from 70, he was about 10 years director of the press.
Late 70s.
To 88.
And during that time, the number of titles per year increased?
Oh, yes.
We've made our first big jump.
in the early 80s, around 82, 83.
And we jumped from the 16, 18, 20 max titles a year that we were publishing then up to about 26 or 28 a year.
And we did that over the space of about three publishing seasons.
So it was quite a well-defined and drastic jump for us.
Describe what that jump meant for those of you on the staff.
Well, it meant a tremendous amount of work, increase in the workload.
We didn't increase the staff that much immediately, although a couple of years later we did hire another editor.
And then gradually the staff began to expand a little bit from there.
But it was...
We had the manuscripts coming in.
We were over the hump of those early years where we were struggling to find good books to publish.
And we were doing some things that maybe we shouldn't have done simply because we wanted to have the numbers of books.
Such as?
Well, some of those books that I was talking about earlier that were by faculty members that really didn't fit any of the
programs that we were publishing in, but we needed the books and we felt that it was a commitment to the university and the faculty to publish those books.
If we hadn't been as
eager to fill out our list as we were then, we might have had second thoughts about publishing those or some of them.
Right.
Now, who made the decision to increase the number of titles per year?
Lloyd did.
And he felt that since we had the good manuscripts coming in, that we ought to just go ahead and
take the bull by the horns and do them.
He went to, let's see, I forget who the president was then.
But I think, actually, I think that was during the period that the press was assigned to the chancellor.
It was actually a system press for a few years in there.
And I think Frank Hubert was the chancellor.
And Frank went to the board of directors or regents, I forget which it was then, and got recapitalization of the press.
Frank Wardlaw had originally obtained capitalization, I think in the amount of $200,000 when the press was started.
And Lloyd went back to the board through Frank Hubert, and they got a commitment from the

board to recapitalize the press and so that also was a major factor in deciding to go ahead and expand the the size of the list as far as you were aware when dr williams became chancellor back in 77 did the press report continue to report to him or did it stay on campus report to jarvis miller
They reported to Jarvis Miller.
All right, that's what I thought.
And how long was he president, two years?
Until 1980.
Okay, so three years.
Yeah.
And I think it was about 1980 then that it was that- To Hubert.
Hubert decided to take charge of the press and it was transferred to his oversight.
And then it went back to the,
to the president I think when Frank Vandiver became president.
As far as you were aware,
Did the press at all suffer during either of those changes, going to the system and then coming back?
In either case, was the press damaged?
No.
In fact, I think it was to our advantage that Frank Hubert took such a great interest in the press.
And he was the person who was most instrumental in getting this building built for the press.
I think we would have languished in those trailers another four years if it hadn't been for him.
He was very interested in what we were doing and felt that we needed a place of our own to work and wanted to see, was willing to put up the fight to see it through.
And I don't think Jarvis Miller would have done that.
You know, I'm making a note to mention to Charles.
I wonder, has anybody done anything to say thank you to Frank Hubert?
You know, like, meaning on a birthday or a Christmas?
Yeah.
Because?
Well, no, I don't know.
We invited him to participate in the 25-year
celebration last year, and because of health reasons, he declined.
See, he's semi-mobile at best.
Yeah, that's what I understand.
I haven't seen him in a long time.
But I've been told that he's not well.
But we wanted to honor him at that anniversary.
And in fact, his name was prominently mentioned in our presentation.
that he was the person who was really responsible for saving the press and getting us this building during that time.
Describe how you recall the process of this building becoming a reality.
It took forever.
We also had an advocate in the university's engineering department.
And remind me the name of the fellow who wanted to save the oak trees during the MSC.
Bob Rucker.
Bob Rucker was our advocate in engineering.
And he had a hand in the planning of the building and the design.
He worked with Lloyd.
Lloyd consulted with all of us.
The staff had a voice in how we wanted the building laid out.

design plans were presented to us and this was the one that we we picked we liked this one do you remember who the architect was not really it's on the plaque by the front door there who selected this location as far as you're aware uh i don't know i don't know i do know though that uh in the original plans

that the big gold mesquite tree in the back was going to be cut down and the building was going to corner of the building was going to be built over that and i said to lloyd why not move the building up eight feet six feet eight feet and leave that tree let it let it live it had been there a long time it didn't need to be cut down wasn't hurting anything and so he he talked to bob rucker and rucker
change the plans.
Was there good staff input into the details of the building on the interior?
Yes.
Like I say, Lloyd consulted with all of us on what we thought we wanted in our offices and how we wanted them arranged.
The plans changed.
Originally the conference room, I believe, was going to be
an open-air atrium.
And then of course that was moved forward and is now the little atrium that is right outside the front entrance between it and the director's office.
But that was originally going to be much longer and run deeper into the building.
When did y'all begin to feel that the A&M Press
was achieving national status, a strong national image.
We felt that we had always had national attention among university presses because of Frank Wardlaw's influence and his reputation.

When we began developing a national reputation, I think was probably with the publication of Frank Vandiver's biography of Pershing, and it was a runner-up in the National Book Awards that year, and I think we began to realize that
Yeah, we're a real small press, and we're down here in southeast Texas, but we can have as much of an influence on publishing and on national letters as any other publisher.
And that gave us a real boost.
That was a tremendous, gave us a lot of confidence.
Did that help to attract manuscripts, you think?
I think so.
I think we began to get military history manuscripts as a result of publishing that book.
And we really hadn't given much thought to publishing military history until we did that book.
And then afterwards, things began to be available that we could pick up and publish.
Now, there is no national ranking of university presses, is there?
Not an official one, no.
That's what I thought.
So there's not a top ten or anything like that?
No, not really.
Among public university presses, Charles and I have done some ranking and we've calculated that we're probably down around 20.
So we're in the top 25, I think.
Top 20 or 25.
Among publics.
Publics, yes.
Of course, we can't compete with some of the private, Chicago, Yale, Harvard.
Now what is their secret to success?
Endowment.
Over many, many years.
And long history.
Yeah.
Is there any one of those that the average well-informed person would identify as the top?
Well, I don't know.
Harvard University Press or Chicago, either one I think.
It depends on whether they're readers in the humanities or in the social sciences.
Which of the university presses has the biggest list of titles per year?
Which one?
among American university presses, not counting Cambridge and Oxford, which of course are like commercial publishers.
California probably has the largest list.
Back to locally, Lloyd is here 10 years, and then he retires, and he's followed by whom, Lloyd Lyman?
Rick Stetter came in, I guess it was 88.
And he's here how long?
Five years.
Describe his director style.
Oh, Rick was very California style, very laid back, laissez faire.
He was a friend of everyone and just one of the most personable people you'd ever want to meet.
Yeah, it was a very California style.
That's about the best way I can describe it.
And then he leaves and he's followed by?
Well, Mary Miller was the interim director for a year and a half.
Okay.
From within.
Yes.
Assistant Vice President for Finance and what's the administration, I guess.
And then she's followed by whom?
Tom Rotell.
And Tom came from?
University of Pennsylvania Press.
And he was here five years.
And then Charles Backus began last summer, about a year ago.
Tom, what was his style?
Tom was a businessman, very businesslike.
And I've learned, I think I've learned more from Tom than from anybody I'd worked for before.
I learned that it's not a crime to think about the bottom line in university press publishing.
And in fact, it's essential that you keep your eye on the bottom line.
And Tom was excellent at doing that.
At the same time, he was a wonderful publisher, too.
He had a really good feeling for books and what was important and what was wanted by both scholarly readers and trade readers.
And he really gave us all a feeling that we were really accomplishing something.
In terms of the bottom line, which have been, as far as you're aware and in press history, the most successful and the least successful books?
Bottom line, in terms of sales.
Sales compared to cost.
Well, of course, I think our best sellers have been the most successful, Landscapes of Texas.
Mm-hmm.
and Fishes of the Gulf of Mexico.
Landscapes is a beautiful photography book, color photography.
It was photographs from Texas Highways Magazine, and we compiled several hundred pages of color photography in one volume, and it's just been tremendously popular for years.
I don't know now how many copies of it we've sold.
I have the sales report right there on the desk if you want to look it up.
Okay.
Okay, this is as of 1st of August.
Landscapes of Texas.
Lifetime sales $43,622.
And you think that's the best seller?
That's our best seller.
Fishes of the Gulf of Mexico, I think, is the second.
Let's see what it is.
All I have here is the second edition of that.
I don't have the first edition, but I think it was up around $35,000 when we
I ended it and published the second edition and the second edition is up around 4,500 copies now.
So close to 40,000 total then.
As far as you and other members of staff would normally calculate it, what would be the number of copies to sell that becomes kind of a break-even point?
Oh, it varies so much from book to book.
It's hard to say.
Can you give some examples?
Well, if you're talking about a very scholarly monograph and you're only publishing at most 750 copies, you'd have to sell at least 650 of them to break even.
And then, of course, the others would be
publicity copies, free copies for review and so on.
So you'd have to sell practically every one to break even.
If you're talking about a natural history field guide and you're publishing 10,000 copies, then probably your break even is going to be around 2,000 copies maybe.
And what about an art book?
An art book depends on the price you put on it.
If you put a realistic price on it and really limit sales, then you could probably break even within your print run.
If you lower the price down to the market demand, then you're probably not going to break even in a reasonable print run, and you need subsidy.
That's why the Moore Texas Art Series Fund is so important.
because that helps us get over that hump and publish those books.
